Line 1
const jwt = require("jsonwebtoken");


This imports the JWT library so we can:

verify tokens

check if they are valid

Without this, the server cannot read or trust tokens.

Line 4
const authMiddleware = (req, res, next) => {


This is a middleware function.

It always receives:

req → the incoming request

res → response object

next → function that lets the request continue

💡 If next() is NOT called → request stops here.

Step 1️⃣ Read the Authorization header
const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;


Here we are checking:

Did the client send an Authorization header?

This is where the token should be.

Step 2️⃣ Check if the header is valid
if (!authHeader || !authHeader.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
  return res.status(401).json({ error: "No token provided" });
}


This means:

If there is no header, OR

If it doesn’t start with "Bearer "

➡️ Then the user is not authenticated

We stop the request immediately.

401 = Unauthorized.

Step 3️⃣ Extract the token
const token = authHeader.split(" ")[1];


Example header:

Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...


We split by space:

index 0 → "Bearer"

index 1 → the actual token

So now:

token = the JWT string

Step 4️⃣ Verify the token
const decoded = jwt.verify(token, "supersecretkey");


This is the most important line.

Here the server checks:

Was this token created by me?

Has it been modified?

Has it expired?

If any of these fail → an error is thrown.

If successful:

decoded contains the data inside the token
(user id, role, etc.)

Step 5️⃣ Attach user info to request
req.user = decoded;


This is very important.

Now every controller after this middleware can access:

req.user.id

req.user.role

This is how:

carts know the user

orders belong to users

admin checks work

Step 6️⃣ Allow request to continue
next();


This tells Express:

“Authentication passed. Go to the next middleware or controller.”

Without this line:

request would hang forever

Step 7️⃣ Handle invalid token
catch (error) {
  return res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid or expired token" });
}


If token is:

fake

expired

modified

➡️ Request is blocked
➡️ Controller is never reached

Final line
module.exports = authMiddleware;


This allows you to:

import this middleware

use it in routes

🧩 How to think about this (important)

authMiddleware is a security guard

No token? ❌

Bad token? ❌

Valid token? ✅ → enter

Your controllers no longer worry about authentication.